Handling outliers:

In [465]:
for c in df.drop(columns='Pass/Fail').columns:
    #getting upper lower quartile values
    q1= df[c].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[c].quantile(0.75)
    
    IQR=q3-q1 #Interquartile range

    lower=q1-IQR*1.5
    upper=q3+IQR*1.5
    
    Outliers=[i for i in df[c] if i < lower or i > upper]
    
    #Calculating mean of the columns ignoring outliers
    
    df_include = df.loc[(df[c] >= lower) & (df[c] <= upper)]
    
    mean=int(df_include[c].mean())
    
    #imputing outliers with mean
    
    df[c]=np.where(df[c]>upper,mean,df[c])
    df[c]=np.where(df[c]<lower,mean,df[c])

logreg = LogisticRegression()

logreg.fit(X_train, y_train)

lr_score = logreg.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f"Score : {lr_score}")

pred = logreg.predict(X_test)
tn, fp, fn, tp =confusion_matrix(y_test,pred).ravel()

lr_recall = round(tp/(tp+fn), 3)   # Of all the people with Chd, how many were recognised to have Chd
lr_precision = round(tp/(tp+fp), 3)  # Of all the people predicted to have Chd, how many did have Chd
lr_specificity =round(tn/(tn+fp),3)    # Of all the people without Chds, how many were recognised to not have Chd
type_1_error = fp    # People without Chd predicted to have Chd
type_2_error = fn    # People with Chd predicted to have no Chd

for name, model in models:
    
    clf = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred = clf.predict(X_test)
    
    cv_results=accuracy_score(y_test, pred)


    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test,pred).ravel()
        #visualization of confusion matrix in the form of a heatmap
        
    cm= confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)
    plt.figure(figsize = (8, 6))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, cmap = 'RdYlGn', fmt = 'd')
    plt.xlabel('Actual Classes', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Classes', fontsize = 15)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix for '+ str(name), fontsize = 15);
    plt.show
    print(name)
    print(classification_report(y_test, pred))
    
    recallv = round(tp/(tp+fn), 3)   
    precisionv = round(tp/(tp+fp), 3)  
    recall.append(recallv) 
    precision.append(precisionv)
    
    results.append(cv_results) 
    names.append(name)
    msg = "%s: %f %f %f" % (name, cv_results.mean(), precisionv,recallv)

Among all the models logistic regression and Decision Tree with oversampling are giving better accuracy and recall. PCA is not giving good results. In our problem recall is more important than accuracy as 94% is class -1 and the other models are not properly predicting the other class.

We will choose these two models and will do hyperparameter tuning and cross validation and then we will select one model.

Conclusion¶

Data had different distributions and contains outliers.

Data has many null values. Some of the columns have more than 50% null values.

Many features are highly correlated which has been removed.

We have tried multiple models Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XG Boost,SVM,KNN AdaBoost.

Among all the models logistic regression and Decision Tree are giving better accuracy and recall.

Classes in data were highly imbalanced.

We have applierd various upsampling techniques and PCA and compared the performance of all the models.

Ranandom oversampling gave better results

We did standard scaling on the dataset and took PCA with n_components as 150.However PCA did not improve either accuracy or recall probably as we were loosing information due to dropping dimensions.

Logistic regression is taken as the final model.

Using feature importance, we found the top important features.
